What is a for Loop?
A for loop is used to repeat a block of code multiple times.

Go has ONLY ONE loop: for
(No while, no do-while)

- Basic for Loop
  for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
    fmt.Println(i)
  }

Parts:
  Initialization → i := 0
  Condition → i < 5
  Post statement → i++

- for as while Loop:
  Go replaces while using for.
  i := 0
  for i < 5 {
      fmt.Println(i)
      i++
  }

- Infinite Loop
  for {
      fmt.Println("Running...")
  }

- for with break: Stops loop completely.
  for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
      if i == 3 {
          break
      }
      fmt.Println(i)
  }

- for with continue: Skips current iteration.
  for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
      if i == 3 {
          continue
      }
      fmt.Println(i)
  }

- for with range (VERY IMPORTANT)
  nums := []int{10, 20, 30}
  for index, value := range nums {
      fmt.Println(index, value)
  }

- Ignore index or value
for _, value := range nums {
    fmt.Println(value)
}

-Loop over map
  m := map[string]int{"a": 1, "b": 2}
  
  for key, value := range m {
      fmt.Println(key, value)
  }
Map iteration order is NOT guaranteed.

- Loop over string
for i, ch := range "Go" {
    fmt.Println(i, ch)
}
Iterates over runes (Unicode), not bytes.

-# Common range Mistake (INTERVIEW TRAP)
for _, v := range nums {
    go func() {
        fmt.Println(v)
    }()
}
❌ Wrong output (race condition)

------ Fix
for _, v := range nums {
    v := v
    go func() {
        fmt.Println(v)
    }()
}

- Labeled for Loop
  outer:
  for i := 1; i <= 3; i++ {
      for j := 1; j <= 3; j++ {
          if j == 2 {
              break outer
          }
      }
  }
Breaks outer loop directly.

- for with select (Concurrency)
  for {
      select {
      case msg := <-ch:
          fmt.Println(msg)
      default:
          fmt.Println("waiting")
      }
  }

- Variable Scope in for
  for i := 0; i < 3; i++ {
      fmt.Println(i)
  }
  i exists only inside loop.

- Shadowing in for
  i := 100
  for i := 0; i < 3; i++ {
      fmt.Println(i)
  }
  fmt.Println(i) // 100

- for with Multiple Variables
  for i, j := 0, 5; i < j; i, j = i+1, j-1 {
    fmt.Println(i, j)
  }

- Empty Parts in for
  i := 0
  for ; i < 5; ; {
      fmt.Println(i)
      i++
  }
  All parts optional.

- Performance Notes (Interview)
  for is very fast
  No difference between for and range in most cases
  range creates copies of values

*** Go uses a single for loop that can act as a traditional loop, while loop, infinite loop, and range-based loop for iterating over collections. ***


















